<TITLE> FAO team stresses seeds and water </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka Mar 29 (bdnews24.com)  Seeds of high yielding varieties, resistant to adverse weather, and improved irrigation are imperative for increasing farm production. A FAO mission, led by country representative Ad Spijkers, after a three-day visit to the south and south-west Bangladesh highlighted the need for quality seeds on Monday. Stressing on the importance of cheap and available inputs, Spijkers said, "Integrated planning of water and agriculture is fundamental for scaling up farm production." The mission visited the largest government seed production facility in Chuadanga, remote islands in Patuakhali, and farming initiatives in Gopalganj. According to a press release on Monday, the mission said that farmers sought quality seeds to boost their production. The team, which included experts from the UN agency's headquarters in Rome and government officials from relevant agencies held that availability of adequate and affordable inputs should be ensured at the farmers' level. "Huge potentials lie in the area for seed production in the fertile fallow lands, but needs good investment plans and farmers' participation," said the FAO country head. Spijkers told a meeting at Gopalganj with government officials attending that the government needed to come up with a master plan to bring back southern Bangladesh as 'the food basket'. "We have to explore the synergies of water, seed and technologies," he 
